{"title_page": "Planned French invasion of Britain (1708)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708\n| partof      = [[Jacobite risings]]\n| image       = File:Jacobite broadside - Coloured portrait of Prince James as young man1.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption     = [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] ca 1708\n| date        = March 1708\n| place       = Great Britain\n| result      = Decisive British government victory\n| combatant1  = [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]]<br />{{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n| commander1  = [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]]<br />[[Claude de Forbin]]<br />[[James Francis Edward Stuart]]<br />[[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]]\n| commander2  = Admiral [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]]<br />Rear Admiral Baker\n| campaignbox={{Campaignbox Jacobite risings}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708,''' also known as the ''''Entreprise d\u2019\u00c9cosse,'''' took place during the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. The French planned to land 5,000-6,000 soldiers in North-East [[Scotland]] to support a rising by local [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]] that would restore [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] to the throne of Great Britain in place of his half-sister [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]]. Leaving [[Dunkirk]] in March 1708, the fleet reached Scotland but was unable to disembark the troops and returned home, narrowly escaping a pursuing British naval force.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|War of the Spanish Succession}}\n[[File:Louis Phelypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain (1643-1727),.jpg|thumbnail|left|200px|The [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], French Naval Minister who co-ordinated the expedition]]\nUnder the terms of the 1697 [[Treaty of Ryswick]], [[Louis XIV]] recognised [[William III of England|William III]] as the legitimate monarch, but when [[James II]] died on 16 September 1701, he reneged on this and proclaimed [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] King of England and Scotland. In response, the English Parliament passed the [[Security of the Succession, etc. Act 1701|Security of the Succession Act]]; in addition to swearing allegiance to William, office-holders were now also required to deny the Stuart right to the throne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=Neville E |title=The Eighteenth-Century Constitution 1688-1815: Documents and Commentary |date=1960 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521091237 |page=340 |edition=2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[War of the Spanish Succession]] began soon after; William died in March 1702 and was succeeded by the last Stuart monarch, James' Protestant daughter [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]]. Since she had no surviving children, the [[Act of Settlement 1701|1701 Act of Settlement]] ensured a Protestant succession by excluding her Catholic half-brother.\n[[File:Articles of Union 1707.jpg|thumb|right|170px|The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely opposed in Scotland]]\nA crushing Allied victory over the French at [[Battle of Ramillies|Ramillies]] in 1706 gave Britain and the [[Dutch Republic]] control of the [[Spanish Netherlands]] but by the end of 1707, the war reached apparent stalemate. Both sides attempted to use internal conflicts to break the deadlock; Britain supported the [[Camisard|Camisard rebels]] in South-West France, with the Jacobites serving a similar function for the French.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=238 |edition=2010}}</ref>\n\nJacobite agent [[Nathaniel Hooke (Jacobite)|Nathaniel Hooke]] convinced French ministers popular discontent provided an opportunity for a Rising in Scotland, which would also help France by diverting British troops from Europe. The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely unpopular while war severely damaged the Scottish economy; French [[privateer]]s caused enormous losses for Scottish maritime trade and the coastal fishing industry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whatley |first1=Christopher |title=Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation |date=2011 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0719045400 |page=55}}</ref> Protecting Scottish shipping was not a priority for the [[Royal Navy]], which faced multiple demands on its resources for escorting merchant convoys.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Lord High Admiral's Answer to the Report of the Committee, upon the Petition of the Merchants complaining of Losses for Want of Cruiz rs and Convoys |journal=Journal of the House of Lords |date=9 January 1708 |volume=18 |pages=405\u2013423 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/lords-jrnl/vol18/pp405-423 |accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHooke visited Scotland in 1707, meeting supporters including the [[Charles Hay, 13th Earl of Erroll|Earl of Erroll]], a fierce opponent of Union and the elderly Jacobite soldier [[Thomas Buchan]], who provided reports on government bases at [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] and [[Inverness]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hopkins |first1=Paul |title=Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724 |journal=Oxford DNB |volume=1 |date=2004 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/3827}}</ref> Senior Scots nobles like the Dukes of Atholl and [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton|Hamilton]] refused to commit, partly due to an attempt in 1703 by [[Simon Fraser, 11th Lord Lovat|Simon Fraser, later Lord Lovat]], to implicate them in a Jacobite plot as part of a personal feud.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lord |first1=Evelyn |title=The Stuarts' Secret Army |date=2004 |publisher=Pearson |isbn=978-0582772564 |page=34}}</ref> However, Hooke obtained a letter of support signed by Erroll, the [[James Maule, 4th Earl of Panmure|Earl of Panmure]] and six others, promising 25,000 men and requesting 8,000 French troops, weapons, money, artillery, ammunition and \u2018majors, lieutenants and serjeants to discipline\u2019 the Scots army.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Presbyterian [[Church of Scotland]] saw a separate [[Parliament of Scotland]] as a guarantee of independence from the Episcopalian [[Church of England]]; despite the [[Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707|Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act]], many feared the potential impact of Union.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowie |first1=Karin |title=Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707 |journal=The Scottish Historical Review |date=2003 |volume=82 |issue=214 |page=229 |jstor=25529719 }}</ref> The supposed Jacobite Presbyterian [[John Ker]] claimed [[Cameronian|radical Presbyterians or Cameronians]] in Scotland and Northern Ireland supported the Stuarts since 'they are persuaded (Union) will bring an infinite number of calamities upon this nation, and will render the Scots slaves to the English.'<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> While the Cameronians were certainly considering this option, Ker was a British government agent paid by the [[James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry|Duke of Queensberry]] whose role was to persuade them not to join a rebellion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Douglas |first1=Hugh |title=John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726 |journal=Oxford DNB |date=2008 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/15449|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-15449?rskey=5nVzQe&result=1|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nLouis decided there was enough support to begin planning in November 1707; this was supervised by the [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], who had been involved with previous attempts in 1692 and 1696. [[Claude de Forbin]] was appointed commander of the naval squadron, with the [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]] in charge of the landing force.\n\n==The Expedition==\n[[File:Claude de Forbin.jpg|thumbnail|left|150px|French Admiral [[Claude de Forbin]](1656-1733) had little faith in the expedition from the start]]\n[[File:George Byng (1663-1733), 1st Viscount Torrington.jpg|thumb|right|160px|British commander Admiral [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] (1663-1733); ca 1700.]]\nAs the [[Royal Navy]] patrolled exits from the French Channel ports, naval operations often took place during the winter months, when wind and tides made it harder to enforce a blockade. However, it also increased risks from the weather; conditions off North-East Scotland were well-known to French privateers and de Forbin's biggest concern was lack of a confirmed landing place. He later recorded that 'the Minister did not mention any port which was in a condition to receive us, ...or where our fleet might anchor and... troops disembark in safety.'<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Based on information supplied by French privateers on conditions in Scotland, de Forbin told Pontchartrain and Louis XIV the expedition would fail, but planning continued.\n\nThe fleet assembled at [[Dunkirk]]; this was a major French privateer base, since they could reach the [[River Thames|Thames]] in a single tide and customarily raided as far north as the [[Orkney|Orkney Islands]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bromley |first1=JS |title=Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760 |date=1987 |publisher=Continnuum-3PL |isbn=978-0907628774 |page=233 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_Ay4tm8zURsC&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=alarm+from+dunkirk+1708#v=onepage&q=alarm%20from%20dunkirk%201708&f=false |accessdate=15 September 2018}}</ref> By the end of February, 5,000 - 6,000 troops, from the French regiments of Bernay, Auxerre, Agen, Luxembourg, Beauferme, and Boulogne plus elements of the [[Irish Brigade (France)|Irish Brigade]] were ready to embark, James himself arriving on 9 March.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=238 |edition=2010}}</ref>\n\nRather than slow-moving transports, de Forbin insisted on using a larger number of small but fast privateers, many of which reduced their crews and offloaded guns to accommodate the troops.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=250 |edition=2010}}</ref> While this improved their chances of avoiding the Royal Navy, the smaller privateers could not hope to defeat British warships in a naval battle.\n[[File:Confiance Kent fight.jpg|thumb|right|180px|British merchant ship (left) battling a [[privateer]] (right); these small but fast vessels formed the bulk of [[Claude de Forbin]]'s fleet]]\nThe British had been monitoring French preparations and a squadron under [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] now arrived off the nearby port of [[Gravelines]]. This prevented the French departure and since James was ill with measles, the troops were disembarked while he recovered. After a week, Byng returned to port for resupply; James and the soldiers were re-loaded and on 17 March the French force of 30 privateers and five warships left Dunkirk.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lenman|first1=Bruce|title=The Jacobite risings in Britain 1689-1746|date=1980|publisher=Eyre Methuen|location=London|isbn=978-0413396501|page=88|edition=[1st ed.].}}</ref>\n\nAlthough their departure was immediately delayed by a two day gale, it forced the British to take shelter, enabling the French to evade Byng and make for the [[Firth of Forth]]. Rather than following the coastline, de Forbin kept the fleet out to sea to avoid being spotted and they ended up north of the proposed landing site. On 25 March, the French anchored near [[Fife Ness]] and spent the next day searching for a landing place, allowing Byng to catch up with them. Despite James' protests, de Forbin's light privateers could not face the British in battle and headed north; they then spent two days attempting to enter the [[Moray Firth]] before giving up.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |pages=255\u2013263 |edition=2010}}</ref> The bulk of the French fleet made it back to Dunkirk, despite being pursued by the British around the north of Scotland and west of Ireland but sustained severe damage to both ships and men.\n\nHearing news of the French fleet, some of the Jacobite gentry, including James Stirling of [[Keir House|Keir]], Archibald Seaton of [[Touch House|Touch]], Archibald Stirling of Garden, Charles Stirling of Kippendavie, and Patrick Edmonston of Newton gathered at [[Brig o' Turk]]. They were arrested, imprisoned in [[Newgate Prison|Newgate]], then later transferred to [[Edinburgh Castle]] where they were tried for [[high treason]].<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=John Oswald |date=1905 |title=Old Glasgow essays |url=https://archive.org/stream/oldglasgowessays00mitc#page/86/mode/2up |location=Glasgow |publisher=J Maclehose |page=87}}</ref> They were acquitted of this charge, as the evidence against them proved only that they had drunk to James' health.<ref name=\"Cobbett\">{{cite book |last=Cobbett |first=William |author-link=William Cobbett |date=1828 |orig-year=1719 |chapter=The Trials of James Stirling of Keir |editor-last=Howell |editor-first=T B |title=State Trials |chapter-url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101049430992;view=1up;seq=712 |location=London |publisher=Longman |volume=XIV |page=1395}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Image:The Duke of Marlborough at the Battle of Oudenaarde (1708) by John Wootton.jpg|thumb|left|250px|By diverting Allied resources, the expedition helped France recapture the Spanish Netherlands but victory at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] restored the Allied position.]]\nPerceptions of the expedition's value reflect a fundamental divergence of objectives between France and their Jacobite allies. The Stuarts wanted to regain their throne; for the French, they were a useful, low-cost means of absorbing British resources but a Stuart restoration would not change the threat posed by British expansion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Macinnes |first1=AI |title=Jacobitism |journal=History Today |date=October 1984 |volume=34 |issue=10 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/ai-maccines/jacobitism}}</ref>\n\nAs with the [[Jacobite assassination plot 1696|1696 Plot]], the 1708 attempt was a response to the dire military situation France faced as a result of [[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlborough's]] victories in [[Flanders]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Szechi|first1=Daniel|title=The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688-1788|date=1994|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0719037740|page=56|edition=First}}</ref> It occupied large elements of the British and Dutch navies for several months, with Byng ordered to remain in Scotland even after de Forbin had left for Dunkirk, while troops were moved from the Spanish Netherlands, Ireland and Southern England.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |pages=268\u2013270 |edition=2010}}</ref> A French army of 110,000 invaded the Spanish Netherlands and recaptured large parts of it, before Allied victory at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] on 11 July evicted them once more. Despite ultimate defeat, for France the expedition largely achieved its short-term purpose.\n\nHowever, in the long run, it arguably damaged both the Jacobites, who had failed to launch an effective insurgency despite popular opposition to Union, and France; in his overview of the political situation in early 1708, Hooke wrote that 'England (sic) seemed to be fully resolved on peace.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hooke |first1=Nathaniel |title=Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains |date=1760 |publisher=Nabu |isbn=978-1247343648 |page=172 |edition=2011}}</ref> The alarm caused by the invasion attempt helped the pro-war [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]] win a majority in the May [[British general election, 1708|1708 General Election]], the first held after Union. This cemented the power of the [[Godolphin\u2013Marlborough ministry]] and the war continued.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bowie, Karin; ''Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707;'' (The Scottish Historical Review, 2003);\n* Bromley, JS; ''Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760;'' (Continnuum-3PL, 1987);\n* Douglas, Hugh; ''John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726;'' (Oxford DNB, 2008);\n* Hooke, Nathaniel; ''Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains;'' (Nabu, 2011 edition);\n* Hopkins, Paul; ''Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724;'' (Oxford DNB, 2004);\n* Lenman, Bruce; ''The Jacobite Risings in Britain, 1689\u20131746;'' (Methuen Publishing, 1984);\n* Lord, Evelyn; ''The Stuarts' Secret Army;'' (Pearson, 2004);\n* Macinnes, AI; ''Jacobitism;'' (History Today, 1984);\n* Owen, John Hely; ''War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708;'' (Cambridge University Press, 1938, 2010 ed);\n* Sinclair-Stevenson, Christopher; ''The Jacobite Expedition of 1708;'' (History Today, April 1971);\n* Szechi, Daniel; ''The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688\u20131788;'' (Manchester University Press, 1994).\n* Whatley, Christopher; ''Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation;'' (Manchester University Press, 2011);\n\n{{Jacobitism}}\n\n[[Category:Cancelled military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of the Spanish Succession]]\n[[Category:1708 in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:1708 in France]]\n[[Category:Cancelled invasions]]\n[[Category:Invasions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions by France|Britain 1708]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708\n| partof      = [[Jacobite risings]]\n| image       = File:Jacobite broadside - Coloured portrait of Prince James as young man1.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption     = [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] ca 1708\n| date        = 1708\n| place       = Great Britain\n| result      = Decisive British government victory\n| combatant1  = [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]]<br />{{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n| commander1  = [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]]<br />[[Claude de Forbin]]<br />[[James Francis Edward Stuart]]<br />[[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]]\n| commander2  = Admiral [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]]<br />Rear Admiral Baker\n| campaignbox={{Campaignbox Jacobite risings}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Planned French Invasion of Britain, 1708,''' also known as the ''''Entreprise d\u2019\u00c9cosse,'''' took place during the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. The French planned to land 5,000-6,000 soldiers in North-East [[Scotland]] to support a rising by local [[Jacobitism|Jacobites]] that would restore [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] to the throne of Great Britain in place of his half-sister [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]]. Leaving [[Dunkirk]] in March 1708, the fleet reached Scotland but was unable to disembark the troops and returned home, narrowly escaping a pursuing British naval force.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|War of the Spanish Succession}}\n[[File:Louis Phelypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain (1643-1727),.jpg|thumbnail|left|200px|The [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], French Naval Minister who co-ordinated the expedition]]\nUnder the terms of the 1697 [[Treaty of Ryswick]], [[Louis XIV]] recognised [[William III of England|William III]] as the legitimate monarch, but when [[James II]] died on 16 September 1701, he reneged on this and proclaimed [[James Francis Edward Stuart]] King of England and Scotland. In response, the English Parliament passed the [[Security of the Succession, etc. Act 1701|Security of the Succession Act]]; in addition to swearing allegiance to William, office-holders were now also required to deny the Stuart right to the throne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=Neville E |title=The Eighteenth-Century Constitution 1688-1815: Documents and Commentary |date=1960 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521091237 |page=340 |edition=2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[War of the Spanish Succession]] began soon after; William died in March 1702 and was succeeded by the last Stuart monarch, James' Protestant daughter [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Anne]]. Since she had no surviving children, the [[Act of Settlement 1701|1701 Act of Settlement]] ensured a Protestant succession by excluding her Catholic half-brother.\n[[File:Articles of Union 1707.jpg|thumb|right|170px|The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely opposed in Scotland]]\nA crushing Allied victory over the French at [[Battle of Ramillies|Ramillies]] in 1706 gave Britain and the [[Dutch Republic]] control of the [[Spanish Netherlands]] but by the end of 1707, the war reached apparent stalemate. Both sides attempted to use internal conflicts to break the deadlock; Britain supported the [[Camisard|Camisard rebels]] in South-West France, with the Jacobites serving a similar function for the French.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=238 |edition=2010}}</ref>\n\nJacobite agent [[Nathaniel Hooke (Jacobite)|Nathaniel Hooke]] convinced French ministers popular discontent provided an opportunity for a Rising in Scotland, which would also help France by diverting British troops from Europe. The [[Acts of Union 1707|1707 Act of Union]] was widely unpopular while war severely damaged the Scottish economy; French [[privateer]]s caused enormous losses for Scottish maritime trade and the coastal fishing industry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whatley |first1=Christopher |title=Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation |date=2011 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0719045400 |page=55}}</ref> Protecting Scottish shipping was not a priority for the [[Royal Navy]], which faced multiple demands on its resources for escorting merchant convoys.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Lord High Admiral's Answer to the Report of the Committee, upon the Petition of the Merchants complaining of Losses for Want of Cruiz rs and Convoys |journal=Journal of the House of Lords |date=9 January 1708 |volume=18 |pages=405\u2013423 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/lords-jrnl/vol18/pp405-423 |accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHooke visited Scotland in 1707, meeting supporters including the [[Charles Hay, 13th Earl of Erroll|Earl of Erroll]], a fierce opponent of Union and the elderly Jacobite soldier [[Thomas Buchan]], who provided reports on government bases at [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] and [[Inverness]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hopkins |first1=Paul |title=Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724 |journal=Oxford DNB |volume=1 |date=2004 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/3827}}</ref> Senior Scots nobles like the Dukes of Atholl and [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton|Hamilton]] refused to commit, partly due to an attempt in 1703 by [[Simon Fraser, 11th Lord Lovat|Simon Fraser, later Lord Lovat]], to implicate them in a Jacobite plot as part of a personal feud.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lord |first1=Evelyn |title=The Stuarts' Secret Army |date=2004 |publisher=Pearson |isbn=978-0582772564 |page=34}}</ref> However, Hooke obtained a letter of support signed by Erroll, the [[James Maule, 4th Earl of Panmure|Earl of Panmure]] and six others, promising 25,000 men and requesting 8,000 French troops, weapons, money, artillery, ammunition and \u2018majors, lieutenants and serjeants to discipline\u2019 the Scots army.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Presbyterian [[Church of Scotland]] saw a separate [[Parliament of Scotland]] as a guarantee of independence from the Episcopalian [[Church of England]]; despite the [[Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707|Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act]], many feared the potential impact of Union.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowie |first1=Karin |title=Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707 |journal=The Scottish Historical Review |date=2003 |volume=82 |issue=214 |page=229 |jstor=25529719 }}</ref> The supposed Jacobite Presbyterian [[John Ker]] claimed [[Cameronian|radical Presbyterians or Cameronians]] in Scotland and Northern Ireland supported the Stuarts since 'they are persuaded (Union) will bring an infinite number of calamities upon this nation, and will render the Scots slaves to the English.'<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> While the Cameronians were certainly considering this option, Ker was a British government agent paid by the [[James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry|Duke of Queensberry]] whose role was to persuade them not to join a rebellion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Douglas |first1=Hugh |title=John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726 |journal=Oxford DNB |date=2008 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/15449|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-15449?rskey=5nVzQe&result=1|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nLouis decided there was enough support to begin planning in November 1707; this was supervised by the [[Louis Ph\u00e9lypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain|Comte de Pontchartrain]], who had been involved with previous attempts in 1692 and 1696. [[Claude de Forbin]] was appointed commander of the naval squadron, with the [[Charles-Auguste de Goyon|Comte de Gac\u00e9]] in charge of the landing force.\n\n==The Expedition==\n[[File:Claude de Forbin.jpg|thumbnail|left|150px|French Admiral [[Claude de Forbin]](1656-1733) had little faith in the expedition from the start]]\n[[File:George Byng (1663-1733), 1st Viscount Torrington.jpg|thumb|right|160px|British commander Admiral [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] (1663-1733); ca 1700.]]\nAs the [[Royal Navy]] patrolled exits from the French Channel ports, naval operations often took place during the winter months, when wind and tides made it harder to enforce a blockade. However, it also increased risks from the weather; conditions off North-East Scotland were well-known to French privateers and de Forbin's biggest concern was lack of a confirmed landing place. He later recorded that 'the Minister did not mention any port which was in a condition to receive us, ...or where our fleet might anchor and... troops disembark in safety.'<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sinclair-Stevenson |first1=Christopher |title=The Jacobite Expedition of 1708 |journal=History Today |date=April 1971 |volume=21 |issue=4 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/christopher-sinclair-stevenson/jacobite-expedition-1708 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Based on information supplied by French privateers on conditions in Scotland, de Forbin told Pontchartrain and Louis XIV the expedition would fail, but planning continued.\n\nThe fleet assembled at [[Dunkirk]]; this was a major French privateer base, since they could reach the [[River Thames|Thames]] in a single tide and customarily raided as far north as the [[Orkney|Orkney Islands]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bromley |first1=JS |title=Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760 |date=1987 |publisher=Continnuum-3PL |isbn=978-0907628774 |page=233 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_Ay4tm8zURsC&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=alarm+from+dunkirk+1708#v=onepage&q=alarm%20from%20dunkirk%201708&f=false |accessdate=15 September 2018}}</ref> By the end of February, 5,000 - 6,000 troops, from the French regiments of Bernay, Auxerre, Agen, Luxembourg, Beauferme, and Boulogne plus elements of the [[Irish Brigade (France)|Irish Brigade]] were ready to embark, James himself arriving on 9 March.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=238 |edition=2010}}</ref>\n\nRather than slow-moving transports, de Forbin insisted on using a larger number of small but fast privateers, many of which reduced their crews and offloaded guns to accommodate the troops.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |page=250 |edition=2010}}</ref> While this improved their chances of avoiding the Royal Navy, the smaller privateers could not hope to defeat British warships in a naval battle.\n[[File:Confiance Kent fight.jpg|thumb|right|180px|British merchant ship (left) battling a [[privateer]] (right); these small but fast vessels formed the bulk of [[Claude de Forbin]]'s fleet]]\nThe British had been monitoring French preparations and a squadron under [[George Byng, 1st Viscount Torrington|Sir George Byng]] now arrived off the nearby port of [[Gravelines]]. This prevented the French departure and since James was ill with measles, the troops were disembarked while he recovered. After a week, Byng returned to port for resupply; James and the soldiers were re-loaded and on 17 March the French force of 30 privateers and five warships left Dunkirk.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lenman|first1=Bruce|title=The Jacobite risings in Britain 1689-1746|date=1980|publisher=Eyre Methuen|location=London|isbn=978-0413396501|page=88|edition=[1st ed.].}}</ref>\n\nAlthough their departure was immediately delayed by a two day gale, it forced the British to take shelter, enabling the French to evade Byng and make for the [[Firth of Forth]]. Rather than following the coastline, de Forbin kept the fleet out to sea to avoid being spotted and they ended up north of the proposed landing site. On 25 March, the French anchored near [[Fife Ness]] and spent the next day searching for a landing place, allowing Byng to catch up with them. Despite James' protests, de Forbin's light privateers could not face the British in battle and headed north; they then spent two days attempting to enter the [[Moray Firth]] before giving up.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |pages=255\u2013263 |edition=2010}}</ref> The bulk of the French fleet made it back to Dunkirk, despite being pursued by the British around the north of Scotland and west of Ireland but sustained severe damage to both ships and men.\n\nHearing news of the French fleet, some of the Jacobite gentry, including James Stirling of [[Keir House|Keir]], Archibald Seaton of [[Touch House|Touch]], Archibald Stirling of Garden, Charles Stirling of Kippendavie, and Patrick Edmonston of Newton gathered at [[Brig o' Turk]]. They were arrested, imprisoned in [[Newgate Prison|Newgate]], then later transferred to [[Edinburgh Castle]] where they were tried for [[high treason]].<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=John Oswald |date=1905 |title=Old Glasgow essays |url=https://archive.org/stream/oldglasgowessays00mitc#page/86/mode/2up |location=Glasgow |publisher=J Maclehose |page=87}}</ref> They were acquitted of this charge, as the evidence against them proved only that they had drunk to James' health.<ref name=\"Cobbett\">{{cite book |last=Cobbett |first=William |author-link=William Cobbett |date=1828 |orig-year=1719 |chapter=The Trials of James Stirling of Keir |editor-last=Howell |editor-first=T B |title=State Trials |chapter-url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101049430992;view=1up;seq=712 |location=London |publisher=Longman |volume=XIV |page=1395}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Image:The Duke of Marlborough at the Battle of Oudenaarde (1708) by John Wootton.jpg|thumb|left|250px|By diverting Allied resources, the expedition helped France recapture the Spanish Netherlands but victory at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] restored the Allied position.]]\nPerceptions of the expedition's value reflect a fundamental divergence of objectives between France and their Jacobite allies. The Stuarts wanted to regain their throne; for the French, they were a useful, low-cost means of absorbing British resources but a Stuart restoration would not change the threat posed by British expansion.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Macinnes |first1=AI |title=Jacobitism |journal=History Today |date=October 1984 |volume=34 |issue=10 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/ai-maccines/jacobitism}}</ref>\n\nAs with the [[Jacobite assassination plot 1696|1696 Plot]], the 1708 attempt was a response to the dire military situation France faced as a result of [[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlborough's]] victories in [[Flanders]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Szechi|first1=Daniel|title=The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688-1788|date=1994|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0719037740|page=56|edition=First}}</ref> It occupied large elements of the British and Dutch navies for several months, with Byng ordered to remain in Scotland even after de Forbin had left for Dunkirk, while troops were moved from the Spanish Netherlands, Ireland and Southern England.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Owen |first1=John Hely |title=War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708 |date=1938 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1108013383 |pages=268\u2013270 |edition=2010}}</ref> A French army of 110,000 invaded the Spanish Netherlands and recaptured large parts of it, before Allied victory at [[Battle of Oudenarde|Oudenarde]] on 11 July evicted them once more. Despite ultimate defeat, for France the expedition largely achieved its short-term purpose.\n\nHowever, in the long run, it arguably damaged both the Jacobites, who had failed to launch an effective insurgency despite popular opposition to Union, and France; in his overview of the political situation in early 1708, Hooke wrote that 'England (sic) seemed to be fully resolved on peace.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hooke |first1=Nathaniel |title=Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains |date=1760 |publisher=Nabu |isbn=978-1247343648 |page=172 |edition=2011}}</ref> The alarm caused by the invasion attempt helped the pro-war [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]] win a majority in the May [[British general election, 1708|1708 General Election]], the first held after Union. This cemented the power of the [[Godolphin\u2013Marlborough ministry]] and the war continued.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bowie, Karin; ''Public Opinion, Popular Politics and the Union of 1707;'' (The Scottish Historical Review, 2003);\n* Bromley, JS; ''Corsairs and Navies, 1600-1760;'' (Continnuum-3PL, 1987);\n* Douglas, Hugh; ''John Ker, of Kersland; 1673-1726;'' (Oxford DNB, 2008);\n* Hooke, Nathaniel; ''Secret History Of Colonel Hoocke's Negotiations In Scotland In Favour Of The Pretender In 1707: Including The Original Letters And Papers Which Passed Versailles And St. Germains;'' (Nabu, 2011 edition);\n* Hopkins, Paul; ''Buchan, Thomas; 1641-1724;'' (Oxford DNB, 2004);\n* Lenman, Bruce; ''The Jacobite Risings in Britain, 1689\u20131746;'' (Methuen Publishing, 1984);\n* Lord, Evelyn; ''The Stuarts' Secret Army;'' (Pearson, 2004);\n* Macinnes, AI; ''Jacobitism;'' (History Today, 1984);\n* Owen, John Hely; ''War at Sea Under Queen Anne 1702-1708;'' (Cambridge University Press, 1938, 2010 ed);\n* Sinclair-Stevenson, Christopher; ''The Jacobite Expedition of 1708;'' (History Today, April 1971);\n* Szechi, Daniel; ''The Jacobites: Britain and Europe, 1688\u20131788;'' (Manchester University Press, 1994).\n* Whatley, Christopher; ''Scottish Society, 1707-1830: Beyond Jacobitism, Towards Industrialisation;'' (Manchester University Press, 2011);\n\n{{Jacobitism}}\n\n[[Category:Cancelled military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of the Spanish Succession]]\n[[Category:1708 in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:1708 in France]]\n[[Category:Cancelled invasions]]\n[[Category:Invasions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions by France|Britain 1708]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "date", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planned_French_invasion_of_Britain_(1708)"}
{"title_page": "Itamar Marcus", "text_new": "[[File:ITAMAR MARCUS.jpg|thumbnail|Itamar Marcus, 2015]]\n\n'''Itamar Marcus''' is a researcher and the founder and director of [[Palestinian Media Watch]],<ref name=brown296>Brown, 2003, p. 296.</ref> which studies [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] society by monitoring and analyzing the [[Palestinian Authority]] (PA) through its media and schoolbooks.\n\nHis work on textbooks led [[Benyamin Netanyahu]] to appoint Marcus to represent his country in the negotiations with the Palestinians on incitement in the Trilateral Anti-Incitement Committee (Israeli\u2013Palestinian\u2013American) in his capacity as Director of Research for the [[Center for Monitoring the Impact of Peace]] (CMP), where he served from 1998 to 2000.<ref name=brown296/>\n\nAs Director of Research for CMP, Marcus wrote reports on PA, [[Syrian]] and [[Jordan]]ian schoolbooks.<ref>Great Britain: Parliament: House of Lords: European Union Committee, 2007, p. 196.</ref>  CMP reportedly broke its link with Marcus stemming from criticisms stemming from disparities in CMP's analysis of Israeli and Palestinian textbooks. \"Incendiary quotations are explained, analyzed, and contextualized in the report on Israeli books; they are listed with only brief and sensationalist explanations in the reports on Palestinian books. In short, the center is fair, balanced and understanding toward Israeli textbooks but tendentious on Palestinian books.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title = Palestinian Politics After the Oslo Accords: Resuming Arab Palestine|last = Brown|first = Nathan J.|publisher = University of California Press|year = 2003|isbn = 0520237625|location = Berkeley and Los Angeles|pages = 236}}</ref>  In February 2007, together with then Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] he released a report on the newest PA schoolbooks at a press conference in Washington.\n\nMarcus testified before the Education Subcommittee of the [[US Senate]] Committee on Allocations, documenting the Palestinian Authority's indoctrination of children to seek death as Shahids \u2013 Martyrs \u2013 for public relations purposes. He has also presented before members of Congress, and to members of Parliament in numerous countries including, the [[European Union]], [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], [[Canada]], and [[Australia]], and has lectured in universities and conferences worldwide.\n\nMarcus is a featured source for the documentary ''[[Obsession: Radical Islam's War Against the West]]''.\n\nMarcus is a former vice president of the [[Central Fund of Israel]],<ref name=\"HaaretzBR\">{{cite news| title = Officials: Israel outsources monitoring of Palestinian media after IDF lapse| author =  Barak Ravid| date =  31 January 2012 | newspaper = [[Haaretz]]| url = http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/officials-israel-outsources-monitoring-of-palestinian-media-after-idf-lapse-1.410082| accessdate = 5 March 2012}}</ref> which won the Jerusalem Prize for Volunteerism. Originally from [[New York City]], he now lives in the [[Israeli settlement]] of [[Efrat]] in the [[West Bank]].<ref>Monheit & Cantor, 2004, p. 69.</ref><ref name=\"JPost\">{{cite news | title = Exposing The Palestinian Media | last=Dovere|first=Maxine  | date = 2012-05-19 | newspaper = [[The Jerusalem Post]] | url = http://www.jpost.com/Features/InThespotlight/Article.aspx?id=270555 | accessdate = 2012-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Brown, Nathan J. (2003). ''Palestinian politics after the Oslo accords: resuming Arab Palestine''. University of California Press. {{ISBN|978-0-520-24115-2}}\n*Great Britain: Parliament: House of Lords: European Union Committee (2007). ''The EU and the Middle East Peace process: 26th report of session 2006\u201307, Vol. 2: Evidence''. HMSO. 9780104011225\n*Monheit, Alan C. & Cantor Joel C. (2004). ''State health insurance market reform: toward inclusive and sustainable health insurance markets''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-415-70035-1}}\n\n==External reference==\n*[http://www.palwatch.org/ Palestinian Media Watch website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcus, Itamar}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli writers]]\n[[Category:Israeli settlers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Israel]]\n\n\n{{Israel-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:ITAMAR MARCUS.jpg|thumbnail|Itamar Marcus, 2015]]\n\n'''Itamar Marcus''' is a researcher and the founder and director of [[Palestinian Media Watch]],<ref name=brown296>Brown, 2003, p. 296.</ref> which studies [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] society by monitoring and analyzing the [[Palestinian Authority]] (PA) through its media and schoolbooks.\n\nHis work on textbooks led [[Benyamin Netanyahu]] to appoint Marcus to represent his country in the negotiations with the Palestinians on incitement in the Trilateral Anti-Incitement Committee (Israeli\u2013Palestinian\u2013American) in his capacity as Director of Research for the [[Center for Monitoring the Impact of Peace]] (CMP), where he served from 1998 to 2000. <ref name=brown296/>\n\nAs Director of Research for CMP, Marcus wrote reports on PA, [[Syrian]] and [[Jordan]]ian schoolbooks.<ref>Great Britain: Parliament: House of Lords: European Union Committee, 2007, p. 196.</ref>  CMP reportedly broke its link with Marcus stemming from criticisms stemming from disparities in CMP's analysis of Israeli and Palestinian textbooks. \"Incendiary quotations are explained, analyzed, and contextualized in the report on Israeli books; they are listed with only brief and sensationalist explanations in the reports on Palestinian books. In short, the center is fair, balanced and understanding toward Israeli textbooks but tendentious on Palestinian books.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title = Palestinian Politics After the Oslo Accords: Resuming Arab Palestine|last = Brown|first = Nathan J.|publisher = University of California Press|year = 2003|isbn = 0520237625|location = Berkeley and Los Angeles|pages = 236}}</ref>  In February 2007, together with then Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] he released a report on the newest PA schoolbooks at a press conference in Washington.\n\nMarcus testified before the Education Subcommittee of the [[US Senate]] Committee on Allocations, documenting the Palestinian Authority's indoctrination of children to seek death as Shahids \u2013 Martyrs \u2013 for public relations purposes. He has also presented before members of Congress, and to members of Parliament in numerous countries including, the [[European Union]], [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], [[Canada]], and [[Australia]], and has lectured in universities and conferences worldwide.\n\nMarcus is a featured source for the documentary ''[[Obsession: Radical Islam's War Against the West]]''.\n\nMarcus is a former vice president of the [[Central Fund of Israel]],<ref name=\"HaaretzBR\">{{cite news| title = Officials: Israel outsources monitoring of Palestinian media after IDF lapse| author =  Barak Ravid| date =  31 January 2012 | newspaper = [[Haaretz]]| url = http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/officials-israel-outsources-monitoring-of-palestinian-media-after-idf-lapse-1.410082| accessdate = 5 March 2012}}</ref> which won the Jerusalem Prize for Volunteerism. Originally from [[New York City]], he now lives in the [[Israeli settlement]] of [[Efrat]] in the [[West Bank]].<ref>Monheit & Cantor, 2004, p. 69.</ref><ref name=\"JPost\">{{cite news | title = Exposing The Palestinian Media | last=Dovere|first=Maxine  | date = 2012-05-19 | newspaper = [[The Jerusalem Post]] | url = http://www.jpost.com/Features/InThespotlight/Article.aspx?id=270555 | accessdate = 2012-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Brown, Nathan J. (2003). ''Palestinian politics after the Oslo accords: resuming Arab Palestine''. University of California Press. {{ISBN|978-0-520-24115-2}}\n*Great Britain: Parliament: House of Lords: European Union Committee (2007). ''The EU and the Middle East Peace process: 26th report of session 2006\u201307, Vol. 2: Evidence''. HMSO. 9780104011225\n*Monheit, Alan C. & Cantor Joel C. (2004). ''State health insurance market reform: toward inclusive and sustainable health insurance markets''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-415-70035-1}}\n\n==External reference==\n*[http://www.palwatch.org/ Palestinian Media Watch website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcus, Itamar}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli writers]]\n[[Category:Israeli settlers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Israel]]\n{{Israel-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Itamar_Marcus"}
{"title_page": "Istv\u00e1n L\u00fclik", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n'''Istv\u00e1n L\u00fclik''' ({{lang-sl|\u0160tevan L\u00fclik}}) (died March 30, 1847) was a [[Lutheran]] schoolmaster in the [[Prekmurje]] region of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]], today in [[Slovenia]], in the 19th century. He lived and worked in [[Puconci]], near [[Murska Sobota]].\n\nThe whereabouts of his birth are unknown. He taught in a school in [[Rajka]] and later moved to the Mura March. In 1833 he translated a textbook from German into [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] and the local [[Prekmurje Slovene]] dialect. One of the topics of this book is the Mura March, which he calls ''Szlovenszka kraina'' in his native language because the inhabitants of the region called themselves ''szloveni'' (Slovenes). In the Hungarian version of the book, he calls them ''vandalus'' (Vandals) because [[Hungarian Slovenes]] living near the rivers [[Mur River|Mura]] and [[R\u00e1ba]] were thought to be descendants of the [[Vandals]].\n\nThree editions of the book were published for use Lutheran schools in Prekmurje. L\u00fclik died in 1847.\n\n==His work==\n* Novi abeczed\u00e1r z- nisteri nemski t\u00e1ksi kni'zecz vk\u00fcp pobr\u00e1ni, i na szlovenszki jezik preobernyem p.&nbsp;L. S. P. S Stampani v- M. \u00d3v\u00e1ri pri Cz\u00e9h S\u00e1ndori z sztroskom Balog Andr\u00e1sa kn\u00edgvez\u00e1r\u00e1\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Slovene writers and poets in Hungary]]\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081024035327/http://www.vasiszemle.t-online.hu/1999/04/mkozar.htm mkozar]\n* Anton Trstenjak: ''Slovenci na Ogrskem: Narodopisna in knji\u017eevna \u010drtica'', Objava arhivskih virov, Maribor, 2006. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081231072401/http://www.ms.sik.si/Vugrinec_Prekmurskislo.htm Digitalna zbirka]\n{{Puconci}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lulik, Istvan}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Slovenian writers and poets in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Slovenian writers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian educators]]\n[[Category:People from Puconci]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n'''Istv\u00e1n L\u00fclik''' ({{lang-sl|\u0160tevan L\u00fclik}}) (died March 30, 1847) was a [[Lutheran]] schoolmaster in the [[Prekmurje]] region of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]], today in [[Slovenia]], in the 19th century. He lived and worked in [[Puconci]], near [[Murska Sobota]].\n\nThe whereabouts of his birth are unknown. He taught in a school in [[Rajka]] and later moved to the Mura March. In 1833 he translated a textbook from German into [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] and the local [[Prekmurje Slovene]] dialect. One of the topics of this book is the Mura March, which he calls ''Szlovenszka kraina'' in his native language because the inhabitants of the region called themselves ''szloveni'' (Slovenes). In the Hungarian version of the book, he calls them ''vandalus'' (Vandals) because [[Hungarian Slovenes]] living near the rivers [[Mur River|Mura]] and [[R\u00e1ba]] were thought to be descendants of the [[Vandals]].\n\nThree editions of the book were published for use Lutheran schools in Prekmurje. L\u00fclik died in 1847.\n\n==His work==\n* Novi abeczed\u00e1r z- nisteri nemski t\u00e1ksi kni'zecz vk\u00fcp pobr\u00e1ni, i na szlovenszki jezik preobernyem p.&nbsp;L. S. P. S Stampani v- M. \u00d3v\u00e1ri pri Cz\u00e9h S\u00e1ndori z sztroskom Balog Andr\u00e1sa kn\u00edgvez\u00e1r\u00e1\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Slovene writers and poets in Hungary]]\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081024035327/http://www.vasiszemle.t-online.hu/1999/04/mkozar.htm mkozar]\n* Anton Trstenjak: ''Slovenci na Ogrskem: Narodopisna in knji\u017eevna \u010drtica'', Objava arhivskih virov, Maribor, 2006. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081231072401/http://www.ms.sik.si/Vugrinec_Prekmurskislo.htm Digitalna zbirka]\n{{Puconci}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lulik, Istvan}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Slovenian writers and poets in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Slovenian writers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian educators]]\n[[Category:People from Puconci]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istv%C3%A1n_L%C3%BClik"}
{"title_page": "Demographics of the Democratic Republic of the Congo", "text_new": "[[Image:Fufuprep.jpg|thumb|250px|Young women preparing [[fufu]] (1988).]]\nThis  article is about the [[demographics|demographic]] features of the [[population]] of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], including [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]], education level, health of the populace, economic status, religious affiliations and other aspects of the population.\n\nAs many as 250 [[ethnic group]]s have been distinguished and named. The most numerous people are the [[Luba people|Luba]], [[Mongo people|Mongo]], and [[Bakongo]].\n\nAlthough 700 local [[language]]s and [[dialect]]s are spoken, the linguistic variety is bridged both by the use of [[French language|French]] and the intermediary languages [[Kongo language|Kongo]], [[Luba-Kasai language|Luba-Kasai]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]], and [[Lingala language|Lingala]].\n\n==Population==\nAccording to {{UN_Population|source}} the total population was {{UN_Population|Democratic Republic of the Congo}} in {{UN_Population|Year}}, compared to only 12,184,000 in 1950. The proportion of children below the age of 15 in 2010 was 46.3%, 51.1% was between 15 and 65 years of age, while 2.7% was 65 years or older\n.<ref name=\"WPP 2010\">[http://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/index.htm Population Division of the Department of Economic and Social Affairs of the United Nations Secretariat, World Population Prospects: The 2010 Revision] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110506000000/http://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/index.htm |date=May 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n!\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Total population\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Population aged 0\u201314 (%)\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Population aged 15\u201364 (%)\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Population aged 65+ (%)\n|-\n| 1950\n|12 184 000||43.7||52.5||3.8\n|-\n| 1955\n|13 580 000||43.8||53.1||3.1\n|-\n| 1960\n|15 368 000||43.8||53.3||2.9\n|-\n| 1965\n|17 54