{"title_page": "Israel Mauduit", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n'''Israel Mauduit''' (1708 \u2013 14 June 1787) was a [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] [[merchant]], writer and [[colonial agent]].  His surname is sometimes spelled as '''Maudit'''.\n\nIsrael Mauduit was the son of a [[English Dissenters|dissenting]] religious minister Isaac Mauduit.<ref>Seed p. 190</ref> His brother was [[Jasper Mauduit]] who was a colonial agent too. He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1751.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27mauduit%27%29| title = Library and Archive catalogue|publisher = Royal Society| accessdate = 5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nMauduit is best remembered for his popular political pamphlet ''Considerations on the Present German War''. The work was an attack on British continental involvement which included the presence of British troops in the army of [[Duke Ferdinand of Brunswick]] and the annual [[Golden Cavalry of St George|subsidies in gold]] paid to Britain's German allies during the [[Seven Years' War]]. The work was first published in November 1760, and went through five editions.<ref>Harding p.184</ref> The pamphlet was released amidst rising opposition to Britain's involvement in the German War. Of Mauduit's pamphlet, [[Horace Walpole]] wrote: \u201cIt was shrewdly and ably written and had more operation in working a change on the minds of men that perhaps ever fell to the lot of a pamphlet.\u201d<ref>Memoirs of the Reign of George III(London, 1894), I: 25</ref>\n\nAfter the Seven Years' War, Mauduit continued to publish commentary on colonial affairs, including several pamphlets during the [[American Revolution]]. One pamphlet, published in March of 1778, advanced the idea of giving the American colonists full independence from Britain. It has been suggested that this tract may have been composed at the behest of [[Frederick North, Lord North]] and his cabinet.<ref>Mauduit p.9</ref>\n\nMauduit later served as colonial agent for [[Massachusetts]].<ref>Anderson p.574</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Anderson, Fred. ''Crucible of War: The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North America, 1754\u20131766''. Faber and Faber, 2000.\n* Harding, Nick. ''Hanover and the British Empire, 1700\u20131837''. The Boydell Press, 2007.\n* Mauduit, Israel. ''A Hand Bill Advocating American Independence, Inspired by the English Ministry''. Ed. by Paul Leicester Ford. Brooklyn : Historical Print. Club, 1890.\n* Seed, John. ''Dissenting Histories: Religious Division and the Politics of Memory in Eighteenth-Century England''. Edinburgh University Press, 2008.\n* Taylor, R. J., \u201cIsrael Mauduit,\u201d New England Quarterly, XXIV (1951): 208\u2013230.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Mauduit,+Israel | name=Israel Mauduit}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Israel Mauduit}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mauduit, Israel}}\n[[Category:1708 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bermondsey]]\n[[Category:British merchants]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:English Protestants]]\n[[Category:English Dissenters]]\n\n\n{{GB-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n'''Israel Mauduit''' (1708 \u2013 14 June 1787) was a [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] [[merchant]], writer and [[colonial agent]].  His surname is sometimes spelled as '''Maudit'''. \n\nIsrael Mauduit was the son of a [[English Dissenters|dissenting]] religious minister Isaac Mauduit.<ref>Seed p. 190</ref> His brother was [[Jasper Mauduit]] who was a colonial agent too. He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1751.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27mauduit%27%29| title = Library and Archive catalogue|publisher = Royal Society| accessdate = 5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nMauduit is best remembered for his popular political pamphlet ''Considerations on the Present German War''. The work was an attack on British continental involvement which included the presence of British troops in the army of [[Duke Ferdinand of Brunswick]] and the annual [[Golden Cavalry of St George|subsidies in gold]] paid to Britain's German allies during the [[Seven Years' War]]. The work was first published in November 1760, and went through five editions.<ref>Harding p.184</ref> The pamphlet was released amidst rising opposition to Britain's involvement in the German War. Of Mauduit's pamphlet, [[Horace Walpole]] wrote: \u201cIt was shrewdly and ably written and had more operation in working a change on the minds of men that perhaps ever fell to the lot of a pamphlet.\u201d<ref>Memoirs of the Reign of George III(London, 1894), I: 25</ref>\n\nAfter the Seven Years' War, Mauduit continued to publish commentary on colonial affairs, including several pamphlets during the [[American Revolution]]. One pamphlet, published in March of 1778, advanced the idea of giving the American colonists full independence from Britain. It has been suggested that this tract may have been composed at the behest of [[Frederick North, Lord North]] and his cabinet.<ref>Mauduit p.9</ref> \n\nMauduit later served as colonial agent for [[Massachusetts]].<ref>Anderson p.574</ref> \n\n==Bibliography==\n* Anderson, Fred. ''Crucible of War: The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North America, 1754\u20131766''. Faber and Faber, 2000.\n* Harding, Nick. ''Hanover and the British Empire, 1700\u20131837''. The Boydell Press, 2007.\n* Mauduit, Israel. ''A Hand Bill Advocating American Independence, Inspired by the English Ministry''. Ed. by Paul Leicester Ford. Brooklyn : Historical Print. Club, 1890.\n* Seed, John. ''Dissenting Histories: Religious Division and the Politics of Memory in Eighteenth-Century England''. Edinburgh University Press, 2008.\n* Taylor, R. J., \u201cIsrael Mauduit,\u201d New England Quarterly, XXIV (1951): 208\u2013230.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Mauduit,+Israel | name=Israel Mauduit}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Israel Mauduit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mauduit, Israel}}\n[[Category:1708 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bermondsey]]\n[[Category:British merchants]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:English Protestants]]\n[[Category:English Dissenters]]\n\n\n{{GB-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel_Mauduit"}
{"title_page": "Tomas Hornos", "text_new": "{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Tomas Hornos\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       =\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{USA}}\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1988|09|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = {{ARG}}\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| retired        = \n| classes        = [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]], [[Star (sailboat)|Star]]\n| club           = {{Unbulleted list|{{yachtclub|Boston Yacht Club}}|{{yachtclub|Cottage Park Yacht Club}}}}\n| collegeteam    = [[Tufts Jumbos]]\n| coach          = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Commodore Hub E. Isaacks and O'Leary Trophies|2007 Matosinhos]] | Snipe }}\n}}\n'''Tomas Hornos''' (born september 15, 1988 in [[Argentina]]), is a world class [[sailor]] in the [[Star (sailboat)|Star]] and [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] classes.\n\nHe was the youngest skipper to win the [[Commodore Hub E. Isaacks and O'Leary Trophies|Snipe World Championships]] by winning the title on his 19th birthday in 2007,<ref>[http://archive.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/09/30/tufts_sophomore_is_champ_skipper/ Boston.com]</ref> and also the youngest sailor to be nominated for the [[US Sailor of the Year Awards]], in 2008.<ref>[https://tuftsdaily.com/archives/2008/01/18/sailing-hornos-becomes-youngest-nominee-ever-for-yachtsman-of-the-year-honor/ THE TUFTS DAILY]</ref> \n\nAfter sailing in the [[Optimist]] and [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] classes, he moved to the [[Star (sailboat)|Star]] class and was the top junior sailor at the 2010 [[Star World Championship]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] ([[Brazil]]). He was third at the 2011 [[Star North American Championship|North Americans]] in [[Tampa, Florida]], and runner-up in 2014 in [[Oxford, Maryland]]. He won the 2012 Western Hemisphere Championship in [[Annapolis, Maryland]].<ref>[https://www.annapolisyc.com/files/2012_STAR_HEMIS.pdf Annapolis Yacht Club]</ref>  \n\nBack to the [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] class, he was [[United States Snipe National Championship|national champion]] in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External lnks ==\n*[https://www.starsailors.com/skipper/141,tomas-hornos Tomas Hornos page. Star Sailors League]\n\n{{Footer World Champions Open Snipe}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hornos, Tomas}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Tufts Jumbos sailors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Snipe class sailors]]\n[[Category:Snipe class world champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Tomas Hornos\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       =\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{USA}}\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1988|09|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = {{ARG}}\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| retired        = \n| classes        = [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]], [[Star (sailboat)|Star]]\n| club           = {{Unbulleted list|{{yachtclub|Boston Yacht Club}}|{{yachtclub|Cottage Park Yacht Club}}}}\n| collegeteam    = [[Tufts Jumbos]]\n| coach          = \n| medaltemplates = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Commodore Hub E. Isaacks and O'Leary Trophies|2007 Matosinhos]] | Snipe }}\n}}\n'''Tomas Hornos''' (born september 15, 1988 in [[Argentina]]), is a world class [[sailor]] in the [[Star (sailboat)|Star]] and [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] classes.\n\nHe was the youngest skipper to win the [[Commodore Hub E. Isaacks and O'Leary Trophies|Snipe World Championships]] by winning the title on his 19th birthday in 2007,<ref>[http://archive.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/09/30/tufts_sophomore_is_champ_skipper/ Boston.com]</ref> and also the youngest sailor to be nominated for the [[US Sailor of the Year Awards]], in 2008.<ref>[https://tuftsdaily.com/archives/2008/01/18/sailing-hornos-becomes-youngest-nominee-ever-for-yachtsman-of-the-year-honor/ THE TUFTS DAILY]</ref> \n\nAfter sailing in the [[Optimist]] and [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] classes, he moved to the [[Star (sailboat)|Star]] class and was the top junior sailor at the 2010 [[Star World Championship]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] ([[Brazil]]). He was third at the 2011 [[Star North American Championship|North Americans]] in [[Tampa, Florida]], and runner-up in 2014 in [[Oxford, Maryland]]. He won the 2012 Western Hemisphere Championship in [[Annapolis, Maryland]].<ref>[https://www.annapolisyc.com/files/2012_STAR_HEMIS.pdf Annapolis Yacht Club]</ref>  \n\nBack to the [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]] class, he was [[United States Snipe National Championship|national champion]] in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External lnks ==\n*[https://www.starsailors.com/skipper/141,tomas-hornos Tomas Hornos page. Star Sailors League]\n\n{{Footer World Champions Open Snipe}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hornos, Tomas}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Tufts Jumbos sailors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Snipe class sailors]]\n[[Category:Snipe class world champions]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomas_Hornos"}
{"title_page": "Quotation", "text_new": "{{short description|Repetition of one expression as part of another one}}\n{{About|quoting text|information about the punctuation mark|Quotation mark|economic usage|Financial quote|7=Quotation (disambiguation)|10=other uses|11=Quotation (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''quotation''' is the act of repeating a sentence, phrase, or passage from speech or text that someone else has said or written. <ref>{{cite book |last1=McArthur |first1=Tom |last2=Lam-McArthur |first2=Jacqueline |last3=Fontaine |first3=Lisa |title=The Oxford Companion to the English Language$ The Oxford Companion to the English Language (2 ed.) |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191744389 |edition=2nd}}</ref> In oral speech, it is the representation of an utterance (i.e. of something that a speaker actually said) that is introduced by a verb of saying. For example: John said: \"I saw Mary today\". Quotations in oral speech may also be introduced using special prosody. In written text, quotations are signaled by quotation marks. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Bonami |first1=Olivier |last2=Godard |first2=Dani\u00e8le |title=On the Syntax of Direct Quotation in French |url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00751080/document |website=HAL |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Quotations are also used to present well-known statement parts that are explicitly attributed by [[citation]] to their original source; such statements are marked with ([[punctuation|punctuated]] with) [[quotation mark]]s.\n\nQuotations are often used as a literary device to represent someone's point of view. They are also widely used in spoken language when an interlocutor wishes to present a proposition that they have come to know via hearsay.  \n\n==Quotations as a literary device==\nA quotation can also refer to the repeated use of units of any other form of expression, especially parts of artistic works: elements of a [[painting]], scenes from a [[film|movie]] or sections from a [[musical composition]].\n\n===Reasons for using quotations===\nQuotations are used for a variety of reasons: to illuminate the meaning or to support the arguments of the work in which it is being quoted, to provide direct information about the work being quoted (whether in order to discuss it, positively or negatively), to pay homage to the original work or [[author]], to make the user of the quotation seem well-read, and/or to comply with copyright law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elc.edu/english-grammar-lesson-using-quotes/|title=English Grammar Lesson - Using Quotes! - ELC|date=2016-11-16|work=ELC - English Language Center|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Quotations are also commonly printed as a means of inspiration and to invoke philosophical thoughts from the reader. Pragmatically speaking, quotations can also be used as language games (in the Wittgensteinian sense of the term) to manipulate social order and the structure of society.<ref>Capone, A., & Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2014). On indirect reports and language games: Evidence from Persian. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 8(2), 26-42.</ref> <ref>Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2015). The secret life of slurs from the perspective of reported speech. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 9(2), 92-112.</ref>\n\n===Common quotation sources===\nFamous quotations are frequently collected in books that are sometimes called quotation dictionaries or treasuries.  Of these, ''[[Bartlett's Familiar Quotations]]'', ''[[The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations]]'', ''The [[Columbia University Press|Columbia]] Dictionary of Quotations'', ''[[The Yale Book of Quotations]]'' and ''The [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Book of Proverbs, Maxims, and Famous Phrases'' are considered among the most reliable and comprehensive sources.  Diaries and calendars often include quotations for entertainment or inspirational purposes, and small, dedicated sections in newspapers and weekly magazines\u2014with recent quotations by leading personalities on current topics\u2014have also become commonplace.\n\n===Misquotations===\n{{further|False attribution}}\n{{Seealso|List of movie misquotes}}\nMany quotations are routinely incorrect or attributed to the wrong authors, and quotations from obscure or unknown writers are often attributed to far more famous writers. Examples of this are [[Winston Churchill]], to whom many political quotations of uncertain origin are attributed, and [[Oscar Wilde]], to whom anonymous humorous quotations are sometimes attributed.<ref>See ''A Book of Misquotations'', edited by Elizabeth Knowles, Oxford University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Trek'' catchphrase \"[[Beam me up, Scotty]]\" did not appear in that form in the original series. Other misquotations include \"[[Just the facts, ma'am]]\" (attributed to [[Jack Webb]]'s character of [[Joe Friday]] on ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''), \"Heavy lies the crown\" from Shakespeare's Play [[Henry IV, Part 2]], \"[[Sherlock Holmes#\"Elementary, my dear Watson\"|Elementary, my dear Watson]]\" (attributed to [[Sherlock Holmes]]; it was, however, said in the films ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1929 film)|The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]''), \"[[Luke, I am your father]]\" (attributed to [[Darth Vader]] in [[Star Wars]]), \"[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Play it again, Sam]]\" (attributed to Ilsa in ''[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Casablanca]]''), \"[[Do you feel lucky, punk?]]\" (attributed to [[Dirty Harry (character)|Harry Callahan]] in ''[[Dirty Harry]]'') and \"[[Stinking badges|We don't need no stinkin' badges!]]\" (attributed to Gold Hat in ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]''). <ref>The Holmes phrase originated in a radio play. See [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/quotes/signature/elementary.asp \"Elementary, My Dear Watson\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>Webb ''did'' say: \"All we want are the facts ma'am\". See [[Just the facts, ma'am]], [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/tv/dragnet.asp \"Just the Facts\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/moments02.html Greatest Film Misquotes - Part 2], Tim Dirks at filmsite.org</ref><ref>{{youtube|nsdZKCh6RsU|We Dont Need No Stinkin Badges!}} although the last of these is spoken by one of the Mexican Bandits that Hedley Lamarr attempts to hire as mercenaries in ''Blazing Saddles''</ref>\n\n==Quotations in spoken discourse==\n===Reasons for using quotations===\n\n===Form of quotation===\n====Quotative markers====\n===Syntax of quotation===\n====Nested quotations====\n====Crosslinguisic variations====\n=====Verbs of quotation=====\n=====Quotative particles=====\n=====Quotative evidentials=====\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource portal|Quotations}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adage]]\n*[[Aphorism]]\n*[[Block quotation]]\n*[[Epigram]]\n*[[Fallacy of quoting out of context]]\n*[[Saying|Maxim (saying)]]\n*[[Musical quotation]]\n*[[Nested quotation]]\n*[[Proverb]]\n*[[Scare quotes]]\n*[[Sic]]\n*[[Use\u2013mention distinction]]\n*[[Quotation mark]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Appropriation in the arts|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Quotations| ]]\n[[Category:Communication]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Repetition of one expression as part of another one}}\n{{About|quoting text|information about the punctuation mark|Quotation mark|economic usage|Financial quote|7=Quotation (disambiguation)|10=other uses|11=Quotation (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''quotation''' is the act of repeating a sentence, phrase, or passage from speech or text that someone else has said or written. <ref>{{cite book |last1=McArthur |first1=Tom |last2=Lam-McArthur |first2=Jacqueline |last3=Fontaine |first3=Lisa |title=The Oxford Companion to the English Language$ The Oxford Companion to the English Language (2 ed.) |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191744389 |edition=2nd |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In oral speech, it is the representation of an utterance (i.e. of something that a speaker actually said) that is introduced by a verb of saying. For example: John said: \"I saw Mary today\". Quotations in oral speech may also be introduced using special prosody. In written text, quotations are signaled by quotation marks. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Bonami |first1=Olivier |last2=Godard |first2=Dani\u00e8le |title=On the Syntax of Direct Quotation in French |url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00751080/document |website=HAL |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Quotations are also used to present well-known statement parts that are explicitly attributed by [[citation]] to their original source; such statements are marked with ([[punctuation|punctuated]] with) [[quotation mark]]s.\n\nQuotations are often used as a literary device to represent someone's point of view. They are also widely used in spoken language when an interlocutor wishes to present a proposition that they have come to know via hearsay.  \n\n==Quotations as a literary device==\nA quotation can also refer to the repeated use of units of any other form of expression, especially parts of artistic works: elements of a [[painting]], scenes from a [[film|movie]] or sections from a [[musical composition]].\n\n===Reasons for using quotations===\nQuotations are used for a variety of reasons: to illuminate the meaning or to support the arguments of the work in which it is being quoted, to provide direct information about the work being quoted (whether in order to discuss it, positively or negatively), to pay homage to the original work or [[author]], to make the user of the quotation seem well-read, and/or to comply with copyright law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elc.edu/english-grammar-lesson-using-quotes/|title=English Grammar Lesson - Using Quotes! - ELC|date=2016-11-16|work=ELC - English Language Center|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Quotations are also commonly printed as a means of inspiration and to invoke philosophical thoughts from the reader. Pragmatically speaking, quotations can also be used as language games (in the Wittgensteinian sense of the term) to manipulate social order and the structure of society.<ref>Capone, A., & Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2014). On indirect reports and language games: Evidence from Persian. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 8(2), 26-42.</ref> <ref>Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2015). The secret life of slurs from the perspective of reported speech. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 9(2), 92-112.</ref>\n\n===Common quotation sources===\nFamous quotations are frequently collected in books that are sometimes called quotation dictionaries or treasuries.  Of these, ''[[Bartlett's Familiar Quotations]]'', ''[[The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations]]'', ''The [[Columbia University Press|Columbia]] Dictionary of Quotations'', ''[[The Yale Book of Quotations]]'' and ''The [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Book of Proverbs, Maxims, and Famous Phrases'' are considered among the most reliable and comprehensive sources.  Diaries and calendars often include quotations for entertainment or inspirational purposes, and small, dedicated sections in newspapers and weekly magazines\u2014with recent quotations by leading personalities on current topics\u2014have also become commonplace.\n\n===Misquotations===\n{{further|False attribution}}\n{{Seealso|List of movie misquotes}}\nMany quotations are routinely incorrect or attributed to the wrong authors, and quotations from obscure or unknown writers are often attributed to far more famous writers. Examples of this are [[Winston Churchill]], to whom many political quotations of uncertain origin are attributed, and [[Oscar Wilde]], to whom anonymous humorous quotations are sometimes attributed.<ref>See ''A Book of Misquotations'', edited by Elizabeth Knowles, Oxford University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Trek'' catchphrase \"[[Beam me up, Scotty]]\" did not appear in that form in the original series. Other misquotations include \"[[Just the facts, ma'am]]\" (attributed to [[Jack Webb]]'s character of [[Joe Friday]] on ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''), \"Heavy lies the crown\" from Shakespeare's Play [[Henry IV, Part 2]], \"[[Sherlock Holmes#\"Elementary, my dear Watson\"|Elementary, my dear Watson]]\" (attributed to [[Sherlock Holmes]]; it was, however, said in the films ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1929 film)|The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]''), \"[[Luke, I am your father]]\" (attributed to [[Darth Vader]] in [[Star Wars]]), \"[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Play it again, Sam]]\" (attributed to Ilsa in ''[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Casablanca]]''), \"[[Do you feel lucky, punk?]]\" (attributed to [[Dirty Harry (character)|Harry Callahan]] in ''[[Dirty Harry]]'') and \"[[Stinking badges|We don't need no stinkin' badges!]]\" (attributed to Gold Hat in ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]''). <ref>The Holmes phrase originated in a radio play. See [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/quotes/signature/elementary.asp \"Elementary, My Dear Watson\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>Webb ''did'' say: \"All we want are the facts ma'am\". See [[Just the facts, ma'am]], [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/tv/dragnet.asp \"Just the Facts\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/moments02.html Greatest Film Misquotes - Part 2], Tim Dirks at filmsite.org</ref><ref>{{youtube|nsdZKCh6RsU|We Dont Need No Stinkin Badges!}} although the last of these is spoken by one of the Mexican Bandits that Hedley Lamarr attempts to hire as mercenaries in ''Blazing Saddles''</ref>\n\n==Quotations in spoken discourse==\n===Reasons for using quotations===\n\n===Form of quotation===\n====Quotative markers====\n===Syntax of quotation===\n====Nested quotations====\n====Crosslinguisic variations====\n=====Verbs of quotation=====\n=====Quotative particles=====\n=====Quotative evidentials=====\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource portal|Quotations}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adage]]\n*[[Aphorism]]\n*[[Block quotation]]\n*[[Epigram]]\n*[[Fallacy of quoting out of context]]\n*[[Saying|Maxim (saying)]]\n*[[Musical quotation]]\n*[[Nested quotation]]\n*[[Proverb]]\n*[[Scare quotes]]\n*[[Sic]]\n*[[Use\u2013mention distinction]]\n*[[Quotation mark]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Appropriation in the arts|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Quotations| ]]\n[[Category:Communication]]\n", "name_user": "FUNG F", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed mistake in citation format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotation"}
{"title_page": "Ismael Mallari", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2015}}\n{{unreferenced|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n'''Ismael Villanueva Mallari''' was one of the early [[Filipino people|Filipino]] writers in [[English language|English]].  He was primarily an [[essayist]]. He is ranked as the leading literary and art critic in the Philippines.\n\n==Education==\nFrom his hometown [[Malabon]] in [[Rizal Province]], Mallari went to the [[Philippine Normal School]] in [[Manila]], then he went as a government pensionado to the [[University of Wisconsin]] (USA) for further studies in English, Education and Library Science. For his accomplishments, Mallari was included in the Pan-Pacific Who\u2019s Who and the Who\u2019s Who library Science. He taught in the Department of Library Science. Later, he worked for the [[United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization]] [[(UNESCO)]] in Manila, capital of the Philippines.\n\n==Personal life==\nIsmael Villanueva Mallari married Natividad \"Nati\" Dolores Quidato Sanglap of San Joaquin, Iloilo in April 1932. On December 27, 1932, their daughter, named Vita Araceli Sanglap Mallari, was born. Two years later, Ismael and Nati separated.\n\n==Writings==\nHe wrote widely and covered a broad range of subjects. His books were usually published under the name I.V. Mallari. \"When I Was A Little Boy\", \"Values\", \"Tales from the Mountain Province\", and \"Footprints on the Sand\" are some of the books that he wrote.\n\n==Opinions==\nIn his ''The Filipino IN English: A Critical Study with Anthology of Representative Essays'' (1912\u20131941), Prof. [[Leopoldo Yabes]] of the [[University of the Philippines]] says: \"While he (Mallari) could not be ranked among the abler critics of the older school, he was conceded by a number of informed persons to be the best writer on problems of Architecture and city planning. He wrote on Architecture with the understanding and skill of a truly artistic temperament.\" Another noted literature, [[Puro Santillan Castrence]], has this to say \"One of the country\u2019s most reliable essayist in English . . . Mallari\u2019s forte in his essays was in his use of simple words neatly and economically. He wrote poems, too.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallari, Ismael}}\n[[Category:Filipino writers]]\n[[Category:People from Malabon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Philippine Normal University alumni]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{ref improve|date=February 2015}}\n{{unreferenced|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n'''Ismael Villanueva Mallari''' was one of the early [[Filipino people|Filipino]] writers in [[English language|English]].  He was primarily an [[essayist]]. He is ranked as the leading literary and art critic in the Philippines.\n\n\n==Education==\nFrom his hometown [[Malabon]] in [[Rizal Province]], Mallari went to the [[Philippine Normal School]] in [[Manila]], then he went as a government pensionado to the [[University of Wisconsin]] (USA) for further studies in English, Education and Library Science. For his accomplishments, Mallari was included in the Pan-Pacific Who\u2019s Who and the Who\u2019s Who library Science. He taught in the Department of Library Science. Later, he worked for the [[United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization]] [[(UNESCO)]] in Manila, capital of the Philippines.\n\n==Personal Life==\nIsmael Villanueva Mallari married Natividad \"Nati\" Dolores Quidato Sanglap of San Joaquin, Iloilo in April 1932. On December 27, 1932, their daughter, named Vita Araceli Sanglap Mallari, was born. Two years later, Ismael and Nati separated.\n\n==Writings==\nHe wrote widely and covered a broad range of subjects. His books were usually published under the name I.V. Mallari. \"When I Was A Little Boy\", \"Values\", \"Tales from the Mountain Province\", and \"Footprints on the Sand\" are some of the books that he wrote.\n\n==Opinions==\nIn his ''The Filipino IN English: A Critical Study with Anthology of Representative Essays'' (1912\u20131941), Prof. [[Leopoldo Yabes]] of the [[University of the Philippines]] says: \"While he (Mallari) could not be ranked among the abler critics of the older school, he was conceded by a number of informed persons to be the best writer on problems of Architecture and city planning. He wrote on Architecture with the understanding and skill of a truly artistic temperament.\" Another noted literature, [[Puro Santillan Castrence]], has this to say \"One of the country\u2019s most reliable essayist in English . . . Mallari\u2019s forte in his essays was in his use of simple words neatly and economically. He wrote poems, too.\" \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallari, Ismael}}\n[[Category:Filipino writers]]\n[[Category:People from Malabon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Philippine Normal University alumni]]\n\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ismael_Mallari"}
